# Economy Basics O/X
> Core ideas about money and the economy
@languageCode: en
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.economy-finance.basic/

Inflation refers to a general rise in prices over time. | O | Inflation means the overall level of prices keeps rising.
When demand rises and supply stays the same, prices usually fall. | X | When demand rises with fixed supply, prices usually rise, not fall.
A central bank can influence interest rates in an economy. | O | Central banks set policy rates that guide interest rates across the economy.
GDP stands for the total population of a country. | X | GDP means Gross Domestic Product, the value of goods and services produced.
Diversifying investments can help reduce risk. | O | Spreading money across assets lowers the impact of any single loss.
A budget deficit means income is greater than spending. | X | A deficit means spending is greater than income.
Banks accept deposits and provide loans. | O | Banks take in deposits and lend money out to borrowers.
Buying a company's stock makes you a creditor who lent it money. | X | Buying stock makes you a shareholder who owns part of the company.
Compound interest means earning interest on both principal and prior interest. | O | With compound interest, earned interest is added and itself earns interest.
Deflation means prices are continuously rising. | X | Deflation means prices are continuously falling; rising prices are inflation.
Supply and demand influence the price of goods. | O | The balance of supply and demand shapes market prices.
Taxes are voluntary donations that citizens may choose not to pay. | X | Taxes are compulsory payments required by law, not voluntary donations.
